In C++, when you're working with file input using `ifstream`, you can check whether a file exists and can be opened by attempting to open the file with the `ifstream` object and then checking the state of that object. The `ifstream` object has a method called `.good()` that returns `true` if none of the stream's error state flags (`eofbit`, `failbit`, and `badbit`) are set. This method can be a concise way to check if the file was successfully opened. Alternatively, you can use the `.is_open()` method which specifically checks if the stream has an associated file opened successfully.

Here's a simple example demonstrating both methods:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ifstream file("example.txt");

    // Using .good() method
    if(file.good()) {
        cout << "The file was opened successfully and can be read." << endl;
        // Proceed with reading from the file
    } else {
        cout << "The file could not be opened." << endl;
    }

    file.close(); // Close the file when done

    // Alternatively, using .is_open() method
    ifstream anotherFile("example.txt");
    if(anotherFile.is_open()) {
        cout << "The file was opened successfully and can be read. (Using is_open)" << endl;
        // Proceed with reading from the file
    } else {
        cout << "The file could not be opened. (Using is_open)" << endl;
    }

    anotherFile.close(); // Close the file when done

    return 0;
}
```

Note:
- Using `.good()` immediately after attempting to open the file also implicitly checks whether the opening was successful because a failure to open the file sets the `failbit`, which makes `.good()` return false.
- Using `.is_open()` directly checks if the file stream has an open file associated with it, which is a more direct way to check if the file was successfully opened.
- It's important to remember to close the file using `.close()` method when you're done with it to release the resource. However, when the `ifstream` object goes out of scope, its destructor automatically closes the file as well.
- In some cases, you might want more detailed information on why opening failed (e.g., whether the file doesn't exist vs. the program doesn't have permission to read it). For these situations, C++ doesn't provide a standard, portable way directly within `ifstream` handling to distinguish these cases. You might need to resort to platform-specific code or check file permissions and existence using other parts of the C++ standard library (like `<filesystem>` in C++17 and later) before attempting to open files.

